THERE WAS A BOY WHO NAMED RONALD.
HE THOUGHT THAT HE WAS VERY RICH WHEN HE WAS ACTUALLY POOR.
THEN HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS.
AT FIRST, HIS SON THOUGHT IT WAS STRANGE THAT HE LIVED THERE.
HE WAS EVEN A LITTLE EMBARRASSED.
HOWEVER, AS TIME WENT ON, HE DISCOVERED THAT IT WAS A GREAT THING THAT HE LIVED THERE.
AND HIS DAD ALSO KEPT THE LIBRARY METICULOUS.
WHEN OTHER LIBRARIES MAY HAVE HAD GUM WRAPPERS AND GARBAGE LAYING ABOUT.
HE EVEN WASHED THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES!
ANYWAY, LIVING IN THE LIBRARY CAME TO BE A GREAT THING FOR THIS YOUNG SCHOLAR.
DURING LIBRARY HOURS OF COURSE HE HAD TO BE QUIET.
AFTER THE LIBRARY CLOSED, HE COULD BE LOUD.
IF HE HAD A QUESTION, HE COULD JUST GO DOWN TO THE LIBRARY AND LOOK IN A BOOK FOR AN ANSWER.
THIS SATISFIED AND FED HIS INTELLECTUAL CURIOUSITY.
HE ENDED UP GOING TO COLLEGE.
THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO ACTUALLY GRADUATE!
AFTERWARDS, HE BECAME A COLLEGE PROFESSOR.
WHEN HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO THE COLLEGE, HE FELT PROUD TO SHOW HIM HIS NAME ON THE DOOR.
HIS FATHER JUST NODDED HIS HEAD IN ACKNOWLEGEMENT.
KNOWING HIS FATHER, HE KNEW THAT HE WAS VERY PROUD OF HIM.
THANKS TO THE LIBRARY, HE ACHIEVED GREAT SUCCESS IN LIFE.
THERE WAS A BOY NAMED RONALD WHO LIVED WITH HIS FATHER AND MTOHER.
HE THOUGHT THAT HE WAS RICH WHEN REALLY HE WASN'T.
THIS WAS IN THE 1940S AND HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY.
RONALD ACTUALLY LIVED WITH HIS FAMILY IN THE LIBRARY.
HE WAS A LITTLE EMBARRASSED ABOUT THIS AS IT WAS UNUSAL.
AS IT TURNED OUT THOUGH, LIVING IN A LIBRARY HAD ITS ADVANTAGES.
OF COURSE HE HAD TO BE QUIET DURING LIBRARY HOURS BUT HE COULD BE LOUD AFTER IT CLOSED.
HIS FAVORITE THING TO DO HOWEVER WAS READ.
IF HE HAD A QUESTION, HE COULD JUST GO DOWNSTAIRS AND GET A BOOK FROM THE LIBRARY TO FIND OUT THE ANSWER.
HE COULD EVEN DO THIS AT THREE O CLOCK IN THE MORNING!
LIVING IN A LIBRARY HAD ITS ADVANTAGES.
HE WAS THE FIRST ONE IN HIS FAMILY TO EVEN GRADUATE FROM HIGH SCHOOL!
HE ENDED UP HAVING A CAREER AS A COLLEGE PROFESSOR.
WHEN HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO HIS SCHOOL AND HIS FATHER SAW HIS SON'S NAME ON THE DOOR, HE LOOKED AT IT AND NODDED.
ALTHOUGH HE WAS QUIET, HE WAS PROUD OF HIS SON.
THAT WAS JUST HIS FATHER'S WAY.
HIS FATHER TOOK GREAT PRIDE IN THE LIBRARY.
WHILE OTHER LIBRARIES MAY HAVE HAD DIRTY FLOORS AND EVEN THINGS LIKE GUM WRAPPERS ON THE FLOOR, HIS LIBRARY, IN WASHINGTON HEIGHTS WAS SPOTLESS.
NO GUM WRAPPERS ONLY WAXED FLOORS.
HE EVEN WAXED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKCASE!
